eventList.name: Mrs. California by Doris Baizley
eventList.summary: First show of the spring semester in the Second Stage Theatre 2019-2020 season
eventList.description:
The time is pre-women’s lib 1955. The place: a Los Angeles hotel, where a homemakers contest is in progress. The contestants are expected to demonstrate the skills of the ideal housewife in an attempt to be crowned as Mrs. California. This play illustrates what can happen when one woman decides to stop doing what she is supposed to do, and starts doing what she was meant to do.  


Tickets are $12/patron (free with a Stetson ID). Reservations are not required, but can be made by calling the box office at 386-822-8700.

eventList.description:
Luca Molnar, MFA, assistant professor of art at Stetson University, will be curating “Over Yonder.” The video art show will feature 10 southern artists who are portraying different landscapes of the south, which examine how industry, gender, race, history and violence have shaped the southern United States today.

Katie Baczeski, MFA, visiting assistant professor of art at Stetson University, will be curating “Clay Legacies.” The show highlights three generations of ceramics and art pieces from the university’s permanent collection, and features former visiting art professors of Stetson and students of those professors along with retired and current professors.

eventList.name: Garniture
eventList.summary: Garniture is an installation by  Madison Creech in tandem with the Oscar Bluemner collection in the Hand Art Center. Bluemner’s drawings and paintings are a field guide to deciphering the wallpaper and textile designs enveloping the walls behind his work.
eventList.description:
Garniture: Visiting Digital Arts Professor Madison Creech presents a selection of Oscar Bluemner's work with a twist. Creech uses content aware technology to create patterns of colors and shapes -- digital collages -- based off of selections from the Bluemner collection. The content aware technology synthesizes existing imagery to fill in gaps in the design. The stylized motifs overlaying each vignette are floral decorations and accessories appropriated from The Vogue Archive from the early 1900s around the time Bluemner phased out his architecture career for fine art. On collaborating with a deceased artist,

Creech responded to Stetson's collection and a selection of texts. Bluemner’s color schemes and textures are preserved while contemporary abstraction tools and The Vogue Archive motifs are stand-ins for a collaborative counterpart.

eventList.name: Garniture
eventList.summary: Garniture is an installation by  Madison Creech in tandem with the Oscar Bluemner collection in the Hand Art Center. Bluemner’s drawings and paintings are a field guide to deciphering the wallpaper and textile designs enveloping the walls behind his work.
eventList.description:
Garniture: Visiting Digital Arts Professor Madison Creech presents a selection of Oscar Bluemner's work with a twist. Creech uses content aware technology to create patterns of colors and shapes -- digital collages -- based off of selections from the Bluemner collection. The content aware technology synthesizes existing imagery to fill in gaps in the design. The stylized motifs overlaying each vignette are floral decorations and accessories appropriated from The Vogue Archive from the early 1900s around the time Bluemner phased out his architecture career for fine art. On collaborating with a deceased artist,

Creech responded to Stetson's collection and a selection of texts. Bluemner’s color schemes and textures are preserved while contemporary abstraction tools and The Vogue Archive motifs are stand-ins for a collaborative counterpart.

eventList.summary: In this workshop participants will learn and discuss strategies in navigating difficult conversations in the classroom. How we manage those discussions, can impact how useful the conversations are to our instructional goals and the dynamics of the class.
eventList.description: Teaching controversial subjects is an inherent part of some courses and disciplines. Topics around identity and values can come up in many fields, and any course dealing with current events presents an opportunity for politically-charged topics to arise spontaneously in class discussions. How we manage those discussions, however, can greatly impact how useful the conversations are to our instructional goals, and what sort of impact they have on the dynamics of the class. In this workshop participants will learn and discuss strategies in navigating difficult conversations in the classroom.

eventList.name: Garniture
eventList.summary: Garniture is an installation by  Madison Creech in tandem with the Oscar Bluemner collection in the Hand Art Center. Bluemner’s drawings and paintings are a field guide to deciphering the wallpaper and textile designs enveloping the walls behind his work.
eventList.description:
Garniture: Visiting Digital Arts Professor Madison Creech presents a selection of Oscar Bluemner's work with a twist. Creech uses content aware technology to create patterns of colors and shapes -- digital collages -- based off of selections from the Bluemner collection. The content aware technology synthesizes existing imagery to fill in gaps in the design. The stylized motifs overlaying each vignette are floral decorations and accessories appropriated from The Vogue Archive from the early 1900s around the time Bluemner phased out his architecture career for fine art. On collaborating with a deceased artist,

Creech responded to Stetson's collection and a selection of texts. Bluemner’s color schemes and textures are preserved while contemporary abstraction tools and The Vogue Archive motifs are stand-ins for a collaborative counterpart.

eventList.summary: Spring Exhibitions in the HAC, focusing on southern artists portraying different landscapes in the south - and - three generations of ceramics and art pieces in the Stetson permanent collection.
eventList.description:
Luca Molnar, MFA, assistant professor of art at Stetson University, will be curating “Over Yonder.” The video art show will feature 10 southern artists who are portraying different landscapes of the south, which examine how industry, gender, race, history and violence have shaped the southern United States today. 

--and--

Katie Baczeski, MFA, visiting assistant professor of art at Stetson University, will be curating “Clay Legacies.” The show highlights three generations of ceramics and art pieces from the university’s permanent collection, and features former visiting art professors of Stetson and students of those professors along with retired and current professors.

eventList.name: Garniture
eventList.summary: Garniture is an installation by  Madison Creech in tandem with the Oscar Bluemner collection in the Hand Art Center. Bluemner’s drawings and paintings are a field guide to deciphering the wallpaper and textile designs enveloping the walls behind his work.
eventList.description:
Garniture: Visiting Digital Arts Professor Madison Creech presents a selection of Oscar Bluemner's work with a twist. Creech uses content aware technology to create patterns of colors and shapes -- digital collages -- based off of selections from the Bluemner collection. The content aware technology synthesizes existing imagery to fill in gaps in the design. The stylized motifs overlaying each vignette are floral decorations and accessories appropriated from The Vogue Archive from the early 1900s around the time Bluemner phased out his architecture career for fine art. On collaborating with a deceased artist,

Creech responded to Stetson's collection and a selection of texts. Bluemner’s color schemes and textures are preserved while contemporary abstraction tools and The Vogue Archive motifs are stand-ins for a collaborative counterpart.

eventList.name: Artist Talk by Eric Anthony Berdis
eventList.summary: Join Creative Arts for an artist talk by Eric Anthony Berdis. View his work here: https://cargocollective.com/ericanthonyberdis
eventList.description: Derived from childhood fantasies Eric Anthony Berdis’ work explores the metamorphosis of a becoming. Set among plush objects and phallic faux-fur sculptures, Berdis transforms into a nonviolent homophobia fighting superhero. Their performance seeks to simulate the jarring experience of being stereotyped while simultaneously examining the ways we navigate towards and create safe spaces. Loud sequined materials are reassembled as uniforms for a dystopic queer world. Each object holds a peculiar function, none of which are to clothe the body or to cover uncomfortable truths. With unrelenting confrontation with the audience they makes the viewer a mirror, and forces one to reckon with their own reactions to what has been crafted as both a worst nightmare and best fantasy.

eventList.name: Garniture
eventList.summary: Garniture is an installation by  Madison Creech in tandem with the Oscar Bluemner collection in the Hand Art Center. Bluemner’s drawings and paintings are a field guide to deciphering the wallpaper and textile designs enveloping the walls behind his work.
eventList.description:
Garniture: Visiting Digital Arts Professor Madison Creech presents a selection of Oscar Bluemner's work with a twist. Creech uses content aware technology to create patterns of colors and shapes -- digital collages -- based off of selections from the Bluemner collection. The content aware technology synthesizes existing imagery to fill in gaps in the design. The stylized motifs overlaying each vignette are floral decorations and accessories appropriated from The Vogue Archive from the early 1900s around the time Bluemner phased out his architecture career for fine art. On collaborating with a deceased artist,

Creech responded to Stetson's collection and a selection of texts. Bluemner’s color schemes and textures are preserved while contemporary abstraction tools and The Vogue Archive motifs are stand-ins for a collaborative counterpart.

eventList.name: Deliberating About Things That Matter: Seeing and Believing: Navigating the New Media Landscape
eventList.summary: The advent of the (now ubiquitous) cell phone camera and of social media platforms has transformed our photographic lives--for good and for ill.  A particular challenge involves the relationship between seeing and believing.
eventList.description: This is more than a problem of "deep fakes" and Photoshopping, though it is that. It also has to do with how photographs (and other visual images) "move" us (emotionally and to take action)--or fail to. With the help of recent philosophically--and theologically--informed work in new media studies and visual culture theory, I explore this problem and suggest possible solutions.

eventList.summary: Join us for the mystery, the wonder, and the amazement that is Mozart's The Magic Flute, a work of profound tenderness and compassion full of joyous lyricism. Both seasoned opera-goers and opera-beginners alike, will marvel at this fairy tale.
eventList.description: Die Zauberflöte by Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart | Stetson Opera Theatre with Stetson University Symphony Orchestra. Join us for the mystery, the wonder, and the amazement that is The Magic Flute! Composed just weeks before Mozart's untimely death, it is a work of profound tenderness and compassion full of joyous lyricism. All ages, both seasoned opera-goers and opera-beginners alike, will marvel at this fairy tale. Full production in German with English supertitles. Pre-performance talk 6:30-7:00 p.m. by Dr. Daniil Zavlunov, musicologist. Tickets available at the door: $10 adult, $5 youth (age 13+), free with Stetson ID.

eventList.description:
Luca Molnar, MFA, assistant professor of art at Stetson University, will be curating “Over Yonder.” The video art show will feature 10 southern artists who are portraying different landscapes of the south, which examine how industry, gender, race, history and violence have shaped the southern United States today. 

--and--

Katie Baczeski, MFA, visiting assistant professor of art at Stetson University, will be curating “Clay Legacies.” The show highlights three generations of ceramics and art pieces from the university’s permanent collection, and features former visiting art professors of Stetson and students of those professors along with retired and current professors.

eventList.name: Garniture
eventList.summary: Garniture is an installation by  Madison Creech in tandem with the Oscar Bluemner collection in the Hand Art Center. Bluemner’s drawings and paintings are a field guide to deciphering the wallpaper and textile designs enveloping the walls behind his work.
eventList.description:
Garniture: Visiting Digital Arts Professor Madison Creech presents a selection of Oscar Bluemner's work with a twist. Creech uses content aware technology to create patterns of colors and shapes -- digital collages -- based off of selections from the Bluemner collection. The content aware technology synthesizes existing imagery to fill in gaps in the design. The stylized motifs overlaying each vignette are floral decorations and accessories appropriated from The Vogue Archive from the early 1900s around the time Bluemner phased out his architecture career for fine art. On collaborating with a deceased artist,

Creech responded to Stetson's collection and a selection of texts. Bluemner’s color schemes and textures are preserved while contemporary abstraction tools and The Vogue Archive motifs are stand-ins for a collaborative counterpart.

eventList.name: "Over Yonder" and "Clay Legacies" exhibits
eventList.summary: Spring Exhibitions in the HAC, focusing on southern artists portraying different landscapes in the south - and - three generations of ceramics and art pieces in the Stetson permanent collection.
eventList.description:
Luca Molnar, MFA, assistant professor of art at Stetson University, will be curating “Over Yonder.” The video art show will feature 10 southern artists who are portraying different landscapes of the south, which examine how industry, gender, race, history and violence have shaped the southern United States today. 

--and--

Katie Baczeski, MFA, visiting assistant professor of art at Stetson University, will be curating “Clay Legacies.” The show highlights three generations of ceramics and art pieces from the university’s permanent collection, and features former visiting art professors of Stetson and students of those professors along with retired and current professors.

eventList.name: Garniture
eventList.summary: Garniture is an installation by  Madison Creech in tandem with the Oscar Bluemner collection in the Hand Art Center. Bluemner’s drawings and paintings are a field guide to deciphering the wallpaper and textile designs enveloping the walls behind his work.
eventList.description:
Garniture: Visiting Digital Arts Professor Madison Creech presents a selection of Oscar Bluemner's work with a twist. Creech uses content aware technology to create patterns of colors and shapes -- digital collages -- based off of selections from the Bluemner collection. The content aware technology synthesizes existing imagery to fill in gaps in the design. The stylized motifs overlaying each vignette are floral decorations and accessories appropriated from The Vogue Archive from the early 1900s around the time Bluemner phased out his architecture career for fine art. On collaborating with a deceased artist,

Creech responded to Stetson's collection and a selection of texts. Bluemner’s color schemes and textures are preserved while contemporary abstraction tools and The Vogue Archive motifs are stand-ins for a collaborative counterpart.

eventList.description:
Luca Molnar, MFA, assistant professor of art at Stetson University, will be curating “Over Yonder.” The video art show will feature 10 southern artists who are portraying different landscapes of the south, which examine how industry, gender, race, history and violence have shaped the southern United States today. 

--and--

Katie Baczeski, MFA, visiting assistant professor of art at Stetson University, will be curating “Clay Legacies.” The show highlights three generations of ceramics and art pieces from the university’s permanent collection, and features former visiting art professors of Stetson and students of those professors along with retired and current professors.

eventList.name: Garniture
eventList.summary: Garniture is an installation by  Madison Creech in tandem with the Oscar Bluemner collection in the Hand Art Center. Bluemner’s drawings and paintings are a field guide to deciphering the wallpaper and textile designs enveloping the walls behind his work.
eventList.description:
Garniture: Visiting Digital Arts Professor Madison Creech presents a selection of Oscar Bluemner's work with a twist. Creech uses content aware technology to create patterns of colors and shapes -- digital collages -- based off of selections from the Bluemner collection. The content aware technology synthesizes existing imagery to fill in gaps in the design. The stylized motifs overlaying each vignette are floral decorations and accessories appropriated from The Vogue Archive from the early 1900s around the time Bluemner phased out his architecture career for fine art. On collaborating with a deceased artist,

Creech responded to Stetson's collection and a selection of texts. Bluemner’s color schemes and textures are preserved while contemporary abstraction tools and The Vogue Archive motifs are stand-ins for a collaborative counterpart.

eventList.name: Access to Opportunity 2: Higher Education
eventList.summary: Come join us for an impactful discussion to delve into the concept of economic inequality in education. This meeting will expand upon the idea that everyone has the potential to learn, but for some it is exponentially easier to actualize this potential
eventList.description:
This event is a professional development training on the concept of systemic economic disparities in higher educational systems.The Participants will engage in active discussion coupled with an interactive activity which will contribute to an understanding of how economic differences can impact one’s education. This meeting will delve expand upon the idea that everyone has unlimited potential to learn, but for some it is exponentially easier to actualize this potential.


This training is sponsored by the Bonner Program. The Bonner Program has been a catalyst for student-led community transformation and social justice at Stetson University. Bonner students work with non-profit partners, each intent on collectively and collaboratively solving challenges in our local and global community. 

All of the Stetson community is welcome to attend this event!

If you anticipate any barriers to your access, participation, transportation to, or inclusion in this opportunity, please contact the Stetson Bonner Program.

Creech uses content aware technology to create patterns of colors and shapes -- digital collages -- based off of selections from the Bluemner collection. The content aware technology synthesizes existing imagery to fill in gaps in the design. The stylized motifs overlaying each vignette are floral decorations and accessories appropriated from The Vogue Archive from the early 1900s around the time Bluemner phased out his architecture career for fine art. On collaborating with a deceased artist,

Creech responded to Stetson's collection and a selection of texts. Bluemner’s color schemes and textures are preserved while contemporary abstraction tools and The Vogue Archive motifs are stand-ins for a collaborative counterpart.

eventList.description:
Luca Molnar, MFA, assistant professor of art at Stetson University, will be curating “Over Yonder.” The video art show will feature 10 southern artists who are portraying different landscapes of the south, which examine how industry, gender, race, history and violence have shaped the southern United States today. 

--and--

Katie Baczeski, MFA, visiting assistant professor of art at Stetson University, will be curating “Clay Legacies.” The show highlights three generations of ceramics and art pieces from the university’s permanent collection, and features former visiting art professors of Stetson and students of those professors along with retired and current professors.

eventList.name: "Over Yonder" and "Clay Legacies" exhibits
eventList.summary: Spring Exhibitions in the HAC, focusing on southern artists portraying different landscapes in the south - and - three generations of ceramics and art pieces in the Stetson permanent collection.
eventList.description:
Luca Molnar, MFA, assistant professor of art at Stetson University, will be curating “Over Yonder.” The video art show will feature 10 southern artists who are portraying different landscapes of the south, which examine how industry, gender, race, history and violence have shaped the southern United States today. 

--and--

Katie Baczeski, MFA, visiting assistant professor of art at Stetson University, will be curating “Clay Legacies.” The show highlights three generations of ceramics and art pieces from the university’s permanent collection, and features former visiting art professors of Stetson and students of those professors along with retired and current professors.

eventList.name: Garniture
eventList.summary: Garniture is an installation by  Madison Creech in tandem with the Oscar Bluemner collection in the Hand Art Center. Bluemner’s drawings and paintings are a field guide to deciphering the wallpaper and textile designs enveloping the walls behind his work.
eventList.description:
Garniture: Visiting Digital Arts Professor Madison Creech presents a selection of Oscar Bluemner's work with a twist. Creech uses content aware technology to create patterns of colors and shapes -- digital collages -- based off of selections from the Bluemner collection. The content aware technology synthesizes existing imagery to fill in gaps in the design. The stylized motifs overlaying each vignette are floral decorations and accessories appropriated from The Vogue Archive from the early 1900s around the time Bluemner phased out his architecture career for fine art. On collaborating with a deceased artist,

Creech responded to Stetson's collection and a selection of texts. Bluemner’s color schemes and textures are preserved while contemporary abstraction tools and The Vogue Archive motifs are stand-ins for a collaborative counterpart.

eventList.name: Artist Talk by Ella Weber
eventList.summary: Join Creative Arts for an artist talk by Ella Weber. View her work here: ellaweber.com
eventList.description: Ella Weber maintains menial jobs, unrelated to the arts, as a means to fuel her practice. Through humor, video, print and the labor of an 8-hour shift, her work draws connections between consumption, the body, sexuality and spirituality.  Residing in fly-over-country, she sleeps in her parents suburban basement and slices meat in a grocery store deli. The deli acts as extension of her studio as well as a tool to reduce the gap between artists and non-artists alike. How do we embrace our differences and share our sameness? Over the counter, she blurs the line between consumer and viewer, performer and employee, the workplace and gallery, art and life.
